<HEADLINE>
<P>
U.S. ADMINISTRATION'S THREAT TO CUT OFF TALKS WITH ARAFAT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At last, in your editorial, you seem to be coming to grips with the thought 
that there may be no justification for the United States to continue 
negotiating with the PLO. If Yasser Arafat does control the terrorist 
organization and its affiliates, then he is responsible for the recent attack 
by the Palestine Liberation Front, one of the PLO's affiliates, on the Israeli 
coast. 
</P>
<P>
If he cannot control these territories, there is no purpose in negotiating with 
him because he will not be able to enforce any commitment he may make. 
</P>
<P>
Arafat insists that he did not know about the terrorist operation, but this 
hardly seems possible since the planning and training for it went on, according 
to Abul Abbas, the terrorist leader of the Palestinian Liberation Front, for 
two full years. This is unbelievable. In any event, the goal of the raid, 
according to one of the captured terrorists, was "to kill civilians in the 
(Sheraton) hotel area of Tel Aviv. . . . We were supposed to land and kill 
anyone we came across." 
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government has already supplied our State Department with 
documented evidence about more than a thousand terrorist attacks against Israel 
since Arafat's pledge in December, 1988, that the PLO was ending such attacks. 
Should it not be clear by now, even to Secretary of State James Baker, that 
Arafat is an unconscionable liar and cannot be considered a credible 
negotiating partner? 
</P>
<P>
You say that whether the acts of the PLO "justify an end to the U.S. dialogue 
with the PLO remains to be determined." But every relevant fact indicates that 
the terrorist PLO has not given up its aim of destroying Israel. Isn't that the 
bottom line? 
</P>
<P>
SOL MODELL 
</P>
<P>
Woodland Hills 
</P>
</TEXT>
