<HEADLINE>
<P>
AMERICAN LEAGUE ROUNDUP; 
</P>
<P>
FIELDER GETS ANOTHER GOOD PITCH TO DRIVE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Good hitters usually hit good pitches and Detroit's Cecil Fielder is proving to 
be one of the best hitters in the majors. 
</P>
<P>
Fielder continued to produce against Cleveland pitching as he hit a 
tiebreaking, two-run homer in the fifth inning that gave the Tigers a 7-3 
victory over the Indians at Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
The homer, on a 1-1 count, came on a forkball from Sergio Valdez that broke 
down and probably out of the strike zone. 
</P>
<P>
"He hit a very good pitch," Cleveland Manager John McNamara said. "You talk to 
other people for advice and we try to pitch him with a lot of care. But he's 
hitting other people, too. That pitch might have been out of the strike zone. 
He just goes down and gets it." 
</P>
<P>
Fielder, who is 12 for 23 against Cleveland, broke a 3-3 tie with his major 
league-leading 24th homer with two out and Tony Phillips on first with a walk. 
He also leads the majors with 59 RBIs. 
</P>
<P>
Fielder has five home runs -- three in one game -- and 11 RBIs in six games 
against Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
Chicago 3, Oakland 2 -- The White Sox climbed to within a game of the 
first-place Athletics in the West by beating Dave Stewart at Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
The game was the first of the season between the teams with the best records in 
the league. The Athletics are 39-20; the White Sox 37-20. 
</P>
<P>
The White Sox have won six of their last seven and 14 of 19. 
</P>
<P>
New York 3, Boston 1 -- Chuck Cary, who yielded six runs in two-thirds of an 
inning Saturday, held the Red Sox to four hits and a run in seven innings at 
New York. 
</P>
<P>
With the score tied, 1-1, Jesse Barfield led of the seventh with a double, took 
third on Mel Hall's groundout and scored on a wild pitch. The Yankees scored 
another run on a single by Jim Leyritz and Bob Geren's double. 
</P>
<P>
Toronto 7, Minnesota 1 -- Pat Borders hit a tiebreaking three-run homer in the 
sixth inning at Minneapolis to help Dave Stieb win his fourth game in a row. 
</P>
<P>
It was the Twins' seventh consecutive loss. 
</P>
<P>
Stieb (9-2) yielded only five hits in seven innings. 
</P>
<P>
Milwaukee 8, Baltimore 5 -- The Brewers blew a four-run lead, then defeated the 
Orioles on Robin Yount's tiebreaking sacrifice fly in the seventh inning and a 
ninth-inning single by Gary Sheffield, who also stole home. 
</P>
<P>
Seattle 5, Texas 4 -- Jeffrey Leonard's two-out single capped a three-run ninth 
inning as the Mariners rallied at Seattle. 
</P>
