<HEADLINE>
<P>
STANLEY CROUCH'S EAST L.A. COLLEGE ROOTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In The Times' recent piece on the black writer Stanley Crouch he is quoted as 
saying he is "a graduate of no college." I believe that to be true, and I also 
believe it to be true, as the quote implies, that Crouch is largely self-taught 
and has achieved his present eminence in literary circles as a result of his 
own abundant energy and talent. 
</P>
<P>
However, in 1965 and 1966 he completed 29 1/2 units at East Los Angeles 
College, including courses in composition, literature, and creative writing. 
</P>
<P>
Of course I don't now what value he places on those courses, but I do know that 
we in the English Department recognized and nurtured his talent. 
</P>
<P>
In the 1965 edition of the college literary magazine, Milestone, we published 
14 pages of Crouch's poetry, citing him for "consistently high quality in his 
portfolio of poems." This had never been done before and has not since. 
</P>
<P>
In addition, Stanley won first and second prize for poetry in our then 
semi-annual writing contest and wrote the introduction to that edition of 
Milestone, a still-impressive and lovely affirmation of the artist's role in 
contemporary society. 
</P>
<P>
SAFFORD CHAMBERLAIN 
</P>
<P>
Associate Professor of English (retired) 
</P>
<P>
South Pasadena 
</P>
</TEXT>
