<HEADLINE>
<P>
ANIMATION COMPANY RETURNS FOR A 2ND RUN; 
</P>
<P>
ENTERTAINMENT: FILMATION IS BANKING ON MOVIES THAT ITS FOUNDER DESCRIBES AS THE 
FURTHER ADVENTURES OF CLASSIC LITERARY CHARACTERS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DON HECKMAN, Heckman is a Calabasas writer. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The flashy ads announcing an animated movie opening next week have a 
bittersweet quality. "Filmation presents 'Happily Ever After,' " the copy 
trumpets, with an illustration that depicts Snow White surrounded by seven 
little "dwarfelles." Yet Filmation -- for years one of the entertainment 
industry's largest animation companies -- shut down its Woodland Hills 
production facility on Feb. 3, 1989. 
</P>
<P>
Why has the Filmation name suddenly reappeared on the entertainment scene? 
Granted, the animation industry has had a startling turnaround in the past year 
or so with the enormous success of "Roger Rabbit" in theaters and "The 
Simpsons" on television. 
</P>
<P>
In late 1988, however, when the film was completed, the animation industry was 
close to moribund. Things looked even darker when the acquisition of Filmation 
by Paravision (a division of the French L'Oreal conglomerate) from Westinghouse 
in February of that year seemed to effectively end the company's 25-year 
production history. The fate of "Happily Ever After," which features the voices 
of Tracey Ullman, Dom DeLuise, Zsa Gabor, Ed Asner and Carol Channing, became 
tied to Filmation's then-uncertain future. 
</P>
<P>
Lou Scheimer, Filmation's former president and one of the company's founders, 
watched in dismay as the film "seemed to slip through the cracks" during the 
complicated negotiations between Westinghouse, Filmation's majority owner, and 
Paravision. 
</P>
<P>
An earlier Filmation theatrical film based on a literary property -- "Pinocchio 
and the Emperor of the Night" -- had been, according to Scheimer, "considerably 
less than a shining financial success." Paravision, with no desire to repeat 
the problem, was primarily interested in Filmation's extensive, and largely 
unexploited, catalogue of 1,500 half-hour shows; Westinghouse simply wanted to 
get out of the animation business. 
</P>
<P>
"When we were in the final negotiations," the 61-year-old Scheimer said. "They 
looked at the numbers for 'Pinocchio' and decided 'Happily Ever After' wouldn't 
do any better. So they figured, 'Well, we'll give Lou this other turkey as part 
of his settlement.' 
</P>
<P>
"But the thing they didn't realize was that 'Happily Ever After' is a much 
better picture than 'Pinocchio' was. It's much less pretentious and much more 
entertaining." 
</P>
<P>
"We learned our lesson with the 'Pinocchio' experience," said Robby London, now 
a vice president at DIC Animation in Burbank and co-author of the script (with 
Martha Moran). "We decided to just have a good time with it, without the 
moralizing and the message, and I think that's exactly the way it worked out." 
</P>
<P>
Whether the film was good or bad, Scheimer found himself without a company or a 
distributor. The vast array of Filmation-produced TV shows -- including "Fat 
Albert and the Cosby Kids," "The Archies" and "He Man" -- had become part of 
the Paravision catalogue. The very name "Filmation" was only usable by Scheimer 
as an adjunct to the title of "Happily Ever After" (reportedly as the result of 
a threatened lawsuit that insisted the film be specifically disassociated from 
Disney's "Snow White"). 
</P>
<P>
"At first," Scheimer said, "I just wanted to get out of the business -- to 
retire. But I kept an office open, and I finally took the picture to the 
American Film Market where I met this guy from Texas -- Milton Verret. He just 
came out of the blue and said 'I want to buy that picture from you.' 
</P>
<P>
"I asked him if he'd ever done anything in the entertainment business before, 
and he said, 'no.' He was in the mail order business, estate liquidators -- 
something like that. I told him, 'You're crazy. This is no business for a 
novice.' But he was determined." 
</P>
<P>
"You have to remember," Scheimer said, "that this was just after Filmation had 
shut down, and animation was definitely not yet back in vogue. So I figured 
selling him the film might be an easy way for me to get out. 
</P>
<P>
"But then Verret started doing things. He made his payments on time. He put 
together an interesting campaign to release the film. And, as many problems as 
he ran into, he kept finding ways to resolve them." 
</P>
<P>
Scheimer's original game plan, during the halcyon years of the early '80s when 
the studio had created a market in syndication for first-run animation with the 
original "He Man" series, was to balance television production with a series of 
theatrical films. 
</P>
<P>
"Secret of the Sword" and "Brave Starr" -- the first releases -- were both 
associated with Filmation television series. "Pinocchio and the Emperor of the 
Night" and "Happily Ever After" were the first installments that Scheimer 
viewed as a continuing parade of films describing the further adventures of 
classic literary characters. Most of those plans were dashed with the sale of 
Filmation. 
</P>
<P>
"But when I saw how well Verret was handling 'Happily Ever After,' " Scheimer 
said, "I began to think, 'Jeez, if this thing works -- if it finds an audience 
-- maybe we can get back to doing more theatricals.' Which is what I wanted to 
do all along." 
</P>
<P>
Whether Scheimer gets his opportunity to check on Huck after he gets off the 
raft or perhaps experience another undersea adventure with Captain Nemo will 
depend on the videocassette and box office response to Snow White's new 
escapades with her seven little Dwarfelles. 
</P>
<P>
"The best thing about the current expansion in animation activities," Scheimer 
said, "is that it proves there's plenty of room in the business for a number of 
players. 
</P>
<P>
"Everybody's been frightened by the fact that Disney's out there, and Fox is 
out there. But the audience doesn't care about the company name. They just care 
about the property. Is it entertaining or isn't it? That's all. We may be 
called Lou Scheimer Productions now instead of Filmation, but if "Happily Ever 
After" is as entertaining as I think it is, we'll definitely be back with 
more." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Lou Scheimer, head of a new production company that bears his name, 
hopes his film based on Snow White will find an audience. JOAN M. ZOPF-PAHOYO / 
Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA061590-0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 234073 </DOCID>
