<TEXT>
<P>
Money Supply Rises: The narrowest measure of the nation's money supply, M1, 
rose in the week ended June 4 to a seasonally adjusted $808.2 billion from a 
revised $803.9 billion a week earlier, the Federal Reserve reported. 
</P>
<P>
A broader measure known as M2, rose to a seasonally adjusted $3,263.9 billion 
from a revised $3,259.4 billion the week before. M1 includes cash in 
circulation, deposits in checking accounts and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is 
M1 plus accounts such as savings deposits and money market mutual funds. 
</P>
